post_text:
The state now is using federal relief money to help individuals and families avoid eviction or homelessness, and maintain housing stability. For eligible renters and homeowners, Minnesota Housing's Covid-19 Housing Assistance Program covers past-due expenses such as rent, mortgage, utilities, insurance, and other housing-related expenses that they incurred after March 1, 2020, but can't pay for a Covid-related reason.

To be eligible, your household income can be no higher than 300 percent of federal poverty guidelines; that means $38,280 a year for an individual and $65,160 for a household of three, for example. There are limits for residents who receive other forms of public rental assistance. There are multiple options to begin applying:

1) Call 651-291-0211. Multilingual staff are available weekdays from 8 a.m.-8 p.m.

2) Apply online at www.housinghelpmn.org/

3) Text "MNRENT" or "MNHOME" to 898-211

Staff will connect applicants to a local administrator. Local administrators review applications, verify eligibility, and handle payments for eligible expenses.

For the Fall 2020 season, Saint Paul Parks & Recreation will be joining the NFL Flag Football League and offering flag football for free! NFL Flag is the country's largest flag football organization with more than 1,000 leagues. In a state with one of the fewest NFL Flag leagues, the Minnesota Vikings are committed to growing the number of leagues in the state, and with that, they will be financially supporting our Flag Football leagues this season to allow all participants to play for free. The increase of leagues that operate NFL Flag will create a more unified version of the game, grow participation at all levels, and create opportunities for children of all ages to learn the sport of football in a fun and non-contact environment.

Learn more about this and other St. Paul Youth Sports at https://www.stpaul.gov/departments/parks-recreation/athletics/youth-athletics/youth-sports-registration-0

The state of MN has launched the P-EBT program for this summer. Applications will open on Monday, June 8th. This program is for students in Minnesota who are normally able to get free or reduced price school meals. Apply and get up to $325 per child to spend on groceries. Children may continue to receive "grab n go" meals or emergency food at COVID-19 emergency feeding sites offered by schools and community locations, even if they are receiving P-EBT benefits.

With a P-EBT card you can buy groceries:
- at most grocery stores
- at most farmer's markets
- online at Amazon and Walmart

Learn more: https://mn.p-ebt.org/en/

The Free Meals for Kids mobile App will help kids and families in need find and access free meals at hundreds of schools and other sites across Minnesota. It is the central resource for statewide information about schools, school districts and communities offering meals during school closures.

The App, powered by GPS, shows locations that are providing meals and meal packs, with days and hours for distribution. It also shows the distance and directions to the nearest site.

post_text:
Even during these COVID-19 closures, students are finding time to care for our community and make the best of springtime. Lydia, an REA senior, has plans to tend to REA's garden this summer with her family (and take care of the chickens while she's at it)! We are so grateful for our community and our students.

Lydia says: "We went down to the school today to start turning up the dirt. Esteban happened to be there in the school and came out when he saw us. We let the chickens roam around as we worked and my mom held one and it was the first time she's held one since she was a teen. My older sister came down to help and we fed them worms and stuff as we found them. She was kinda scared of them at first. We got some chicken feed from Fleet Farm to bring down to feed them when we're down there."

Youth MOVE MN has launched Youth Voices of Experience, a new monthly online magazine and podcast that amplifies the voices of youth who are raising awareness about mental health. Youth MOVE MN is a statewide youth-led program committed to sharing their stories to improve mental health, education, child welfare, and criminal justice systems.

Youth Voices of Experience’s launch on www.youthmove-mn.org on Thursday, May 7 coincides with National Children’s Mental Health Awareness Day.

The first issue of the online magazine features a short story by Emma Warmanen, a dance work by Cathy Truong, and visual art by Lidija Namike, Long Nguyen, Jane Rohlfing, and Jarrett Vanderpoel.

“We can show youth that they aren't alone, and provide hope for any young person struggling,” says VanderPoel, age 18, of Cloquet, MN. “We can show them that what they're feeling or experiencing is nothing to be ashamed of and that there is help available.”

This means school will be closed through March 16th-March 27th. Spring breaks for all sites will continue to be scheduled as planned. We will continue to follow guidance from the state as we make decisions that are in the best interest of our students, families, staff and the public.

post_text:
Minnesota has launched a State-wide number to call for a mental health crisis: **CRISIS (**274747)

By calling this number you will be seamlessly forwarded to a county crisis team based on your call's location for support by phone, or when needed, to have a team meet you to provide support. Teams provide rapid response and work to assess the individual, resolve crises and link people to needed services. They are available in all parts of the state 24 hours a day, seven days a week.

Roll out is happening incrementally. Piloting has just been completed in the Twin Cities. As the system rolls out, a landline 800 number will be added for people without cell phones.

Roll out is happening incrementally. Piloting has just been completed in the Twin Cities. As the system rolls out, a landline 800 number will be added for people without cell phones.

post_text: STEM Freedom School and St Paul City School scholars visit the Capitol! This past summer, CDF Freedom School scholars were able to march for gun violence awareness for our National Day of Social Action. On Thursday, scholars were able to have a discussion with legislators on the topic of gun violence and after school programming. Scholars were able to meet the legislator whom represents their city zone and ask questions about how they plan to make a difference. This was a great opportunity for scholars to really have their voices heard.

Friends of SPCS! Are you a youth looking for a summer job or internship? Apply to Saint Paul's Right Track program! Applications can be sent in beginning this Saturday, Feb. 1 and the last day to apply is Saturday Feb. 29. Right Track provides summer employment to Saint Paul residents ages 14-24 who live in cost-burdened households or have a barrier to employment. Most internships begin on June 22 and run 6-9 weeks.

https://righttrack-app.stpaul.gov/

Remember fortune tellers from elementary school? Students at REA put a twist on them in Crew this morning as a fun way to discuss healthy coping skills! Instead of getting a fortune when you pick a number, you get a suggestion for a coping skill to practice in times of stress or frustration. This lesson is the 2nd in a series of lessons this week that are centered around mental wellness.

Crew is an important part of each day at REA. Each student is in a Crew and they start each day with this group. Crew is a time for community building, health awareness, fitness, college & career preparedness, and service learning.

River's Edge Academy high schoolers are out visiting colleges today for Fieldwork! This group made it to the U of M - Twin Cities today. Other groups went to Inver Hills Community College, Metro State, and St. Kates.

What's Fieldwork? Every Wednesday at REA, students leave the building on field trips related to what they're learning in school. Fieldwork typically includes things like museum visits, guest speakers, tours, community service, or - like today - College Visits! Fieldwork is an important part of REA's focus on experiential learning.

Good Evening SPCS Familes! We are very sorry to inform you that due to weather there will be NO SCHOOL tomorrow, Friday, February 8th. While we do not want to miss any more days of school, our first priority is the safety of our students! With tomorrow's extreme cold temperatures and snow covered roads we want students to stay home and be safe!

Buenas noches SPCS familias! Lamentamos informarle que, debido al clima, NO HABRÁ CLASES mañana, viernes 8 de febrero. Si bien no queremos perder más días de clases, nuestra prioridad es la seguridad de nuestros estudiantes. Con las temperaturas frías extremas y los caminos cubiertos de nieve del mañana, queremos que los estudiantes se queden en casa y estén seguros.

Here are some wonderful things to mention to potential families:
-We had our highest academics in 20 years last year!
-We had the highest middle school math achievement yet in 2017-18!
-We have reduced suspensions by 85% over the past 2 years!
-A Star tribune article named SPCS middle school as a "Beating the Odds" school for academic achievement!
-We have FREE Academically focused enrichment programming Monday-Thursday!
-We have our Center for Culture, Families & Learning - That is designed around helping families through our partnership with SPPN!
